# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electronic-warfare
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Modern military forces use chaff to distract active radar homing missiles from their targets.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Military aircraft and warships can be equipped with chaff dispensing systems for self-defense.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] During its midcourse phase, an intercontinental ballistic missile may release chaff along with its other penetration aids.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Contemporary radar systems can distinguish chaff from legitimate targets by measuring the Doppler effect; chaff quickly loses speed after leaving an aircraft, and the resulting shift in wavelength of the radar return can be measured.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] To counter this, a chaff cloud can be illuminated by the defending vehicle with a doppler-corrected frequency.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] This is known as JAFF (jammer plus chaff) or CHILL (chaff-illuminated).
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The idea of using chaff developed independently in the United Kingdom, Germany, the United States and Japan.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] In 1937, British researcher Gerald Touch, while working with Robert Watson-Watt on radar, suggested that lengths of wire suspended from balloons or parachutes might overwhelm a radar system with false echoes and R.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Jones had suggested that pieces of metal foil falling through the air might do the same.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] In early 1942, Telecommunications Research Establishment (TRE) researcher Joan Curran investigated the idea and came up with a scheme for dumping packets of aluminium strips from aircraft to generate a cloud of false echoes.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] An early idea was to use sheets the size of a notebook page; these would be printed so they would also serve as propaganda leaflets.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] It was found that the most effective version was strips of black paper backed with aluminium foil, exactly 27 cm × 2 cm (10.63 in × 0.79 in) and packed into bundles each weighing 1 pound (0.45 kg).
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] In Germany, similar research had led to the development of *Düppel*.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The German code name came from the estate where the first German tests with chaff took place, circa 1942.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Once the British had passed the idea to the US via the Tizard Mission, Fred Whipple developed a system for dispensing strips for the USAAF, but it is not known if this was ever used.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The systems used the same concept of small aluminium strips (or wires) cut to a half of the target radar's wavelength.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] When hit by the radar, such lengths of metal resonate and re-radiate the signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Opposing defences would find it almost impossible to distinguish the aircraft from the echoes caused by the chaff.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Other radar-confusing techniques included airborne jamming devices codenamed Mandrel, Piperack, Jostle and Carpet.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Mandrel was an airborne jammer targeted at the German Freya radars, while Carpet targeted the gun-laying Würzburg radar.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Ignorance about the extent of knowledge of the principle in the opposing air force led planners to judge that it was too dangerous to use, since the opponent could duplicate it.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The British government's leading scientific adviser, Professor Lindemann, pointed out that if the Royal Air Force (RAF) used it against the Germans, the *Luftwaffe* would quickly copy it and could launch a new Blitz.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] This caused concern in RAF Fighter Command and Anti-Aircraft Command, who managed to suppress the use of Window until July 1943.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] It was felt that the new generation of centimetric radars available to Fighter Command would cope with *Luftwaffe* retaliation.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Examination of the Würzburg radar equipment brought back to the UK during Operation Biting (February 1942) and subsequent reconnaissance revealed to the British that all German radars were operating in no more than three frequency ranges, making them prone to jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Arthur Travers "Bomber" Harris, Commander-in-Chief (C-in-C) of RAF Bomber Command, finally got approval to use Window as part of Operation Gomorrah, the week long bombing campaign against Hamburg.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The first aircrew trained to use Window were in 76 Squadron.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Twenty-four crews were briefed on how to drop the bundles of aluminised-paper strips (treated-paper was used to minimise the weight and to maximise the time that the strips would remain in the air, prolonging the effect), one every minute through the flare chute, using a stopwatch to time them.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The radar-guided master searchlights wandered aimlessly across the sky.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The anti-aircraft guns fired randomly or not at all and the night fighters, their radar displays swamped with false echoes, utterly failed to find the bomber stream.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] For over a week, Allied attacks devastated a vast area of Hamburg, resulting in more than 40,000 civilian deaths, with the loss of only 12 out of the 791 bombers on the first night.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Squadrons quickly had special chutes fitted to their bombers to make chaff deployment even easier.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Seeing this as a development that made it safer to go on operations, many crews got in as many trips as they could before the Germans found a counter-countermeasure.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Although the metal strips puzzled the German civilians at first, German scientists knew exactly what they were–*Düppel*—but had refrained from using it for the same reasons as Lindemann had pointed out to the British.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] For over a year the curious situation arose where both sides of the conflict knew how to use chaff to jam the other side's radar but had refrained from doing so for fear of their opponent replying in kind.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] *Oberst* Hajo Herrmann developed *Wilde Sau* (Wild Boar) to cope with the lack of accurate ground guidance and led to the formation of three new fighter wings to use the tactic, numbered JG 300, JG 301 and JG 302.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Ground operators would radio-direct single-seat fighters and night fighters to areas where the concentrations of chaff were greatest (which would indicate the source of the chaff) for the fighter pilots to see targets, often against the illumination from fires and searchlights below.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] A few of the single-seat fighters had the FuG 350 *Naxos* device to detect H2S radar (the first airborne, ground scanning radar system) emissions from the bombers.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Six weeks after the Hamburg raid, the *Luftwaffe* used *Düppel* in 80 cm × 1.9 cm (31.50 in × 0.75 in) lengths during a raid on the night of 7/8 October 1943.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] In raids in 1943 and the "mini-blitz" of Operation Steinbock between February and May 1944, *Düppel* allowed German bombers again to attempt operations over London.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Although theoretically effective, the small number of bombers, notably in relation to the large RAF night-fighter force, doomed the effort from the start.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The British fighters were able to go aloft in large numbers and often found the German bombers in spite of *Düppel*.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The Germans obtained better results during the air raid on Bari in Italy, on 2 December 1943, when Allied radars were deceived by the use of *Düppel*.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Following the British discovery of it in 1942 by Joan Curran, chaff in the United States was co-invented by astronomer Fred Whipple and Navy engineer Merwyn Bly.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Whipple proposed the idea to the Air Force he was working with at the time.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Early tests failed as the foil strips stuck together and fell as clumps to little or no effect.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Bly solved this by designing a cartridge that forced the strips to rub against it as they were expelled, gaining an electrostatic charge.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Since the strips all had a similar charge they repelled each other, enabling the full countermeasure effect.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] After the war, Bly received the Navy Distinguished Civilian Service Award for his work.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] In the Pacific Theatre, Navy Lieutenant Commander Sudo Hajime invented a Japanese version called *Giman-shi*, or "deceiving paper".
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] It was first used with some success in mid 1943, during night battles over the Solomon Islands.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Competing demands for the scarce aluminum necessary for its manufacture limited its use.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] On February 21, 1945, during the Battle of Iwo Jima, *Giman-shi* was successfully used prior to a Kamikaze attack on the USS *Saratoga*.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] British warships in the Falklands War (1982) made heavy use of chaff.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] During this war, British Sea Harrier aircraft lacked their conventional chaff-dispensing mechanism.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Therefore, Royal Navy engineers designed an improvised delivery system of welding rods, split pins and string, which allowed six packets of chaff to be stored in the airbrake well and be deployed in flight.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] It was often referred to as the "Heath Robinson chaff modification", due to its complexity.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Although chaff produces large amounts of scattered reflections potentially clogging a radar display it can filtered through multiple methods such as tracking its altitude and through the doppler effect.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Radar can make use of the doppler effect to distinguish between chaff and target aircraft which are fast moving.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The doppler effect only occurs for the component of velocity parallel to the radar beam.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] To overcome this, large amounts of chaff are deployed and then the aircraft will turn so that it moves predominantly perpendicular to the radar source.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] It may also rotate to minimize its cross section exposed to the radar beam.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] This leads to aircraft being more difficult to separate from the effectively stationary chaff and is known as "notching" as radar typically incorporate a notch of low sensitivity to frequencies associated with low velocity.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The effect is likely to be momentary against modern radar systems but can be prolonged by the use of Chill and Jaff as described below.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Another method described by a meteorological journal describes the use of the chaff's altitude and descent as another method of removing large clusters of chaff from clogging radar readings.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] This method, however, is unreliable due to potential weather conditions, so it is most optimally used during clear skies.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] One of the important qualities of chaff is that it is lightweight, allowing large amounts to be carried.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] As a result, after release it quickly loses any forward speed it had from the aircraft or rocket launcher, and then begins to fall slowly to the ground.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] From the viewpoint of an enemy radar, the chaff quickly decays to zero velocity.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Modern radars use the Doppler effect to measure the line-of-sight velocity of objects, and can thus distinguish chaff from an aircraft, which continues to move at high speed.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] This allows the radar to filter out the chaff from its display.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] To counteract this filtering, the JAFF or CHILL technique has been developed.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] This uses an additional jammer broadcaster on the aircraft to reflect a signal off the chaff cloud that has the proper frequency to match that of the aircraft.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] This makes it impossible to use Doppler shift alone to filter out the chaff signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] In practice, the signal is deliberately noisy in order to present multiple false targets.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] In essence, the JAFF technique is a low-cost offboard decoy, moving the jammers from the launcher platform to the decoy, and using the chaff as a reflector to provide angular separation.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] While foil chaff is still used by certain aircraft, such as the Boeing B-52 Stratofortress bomber, this type is no longer manufactured.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The chaff used by aircraft such as the Fairchild-Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II, McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle, General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon, and McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornet consists of aluminium-coated glass fibres.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] These fibre "dipoles" are designed to remain airborne for as long as possible, having a typical diameter of 1 mil, or 0.025 mm, and a typical length of 0.3 inches (7.6 mm) to over 2 inches (51 mm).
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Newer "superfine" chaff has a typical diameter of 0.7 mils (0.018 mm).
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The chaff is carried in tubular cartridges, which remain attached to the aircraft, each typically containing around 3 to 5 million chaff fibres.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] The chaff is ejected from the cartridge by a plastic piston driven by a small pyrotechnic charge.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Chaff countermeasures come in two main types: continuous wave (CW) chaff, used against radar-guided missiles that operate on a continuous frequency, and pulsed chaff, used against missiles that operate on a pulsed frequency.
[src:electronic-warfare/chaff-countermeasure] Little research has been conducted on the public health and environmental effects of chaff.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] RDF systems can be used with any radio source, although very long wavelengths (low frequencies) require very large antennas, and are generally used only on ground-based systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These wavelengths are nevertheless used for marine radio navigation as they can travel very long distances "over the horizon", which is valuable for ships when the line-of-sight may be only a few tens of kilometres.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For aerial use, where the horizon may extend to hundreds of kilometres, higher frequencies can be used, allowing the use of much smaller antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] An automatic direction finder, which could be tuned to radio beacons called non-directional beacons or commercial AM radio broadcasters, was in the 20th century a feature of most aircraft, but is being phased out.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For the military, RDF is a key tool of signals intelligence.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The ability to locate the position of an enemy transmitter has been invaluable since World War I, and played a key role in World War II's Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] It is estimated that the UK's advanced "huff-duff" systems were directly or indirectly responsible for 24% of all U-boats sunk during the war.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Modern systems often used phased array antennas to allow rapid beamforming for highly accurate results, and are part of a larger electronic warfare suite.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Early radio direction finders used mechanically rotated antennas that compared signal strengths, and several electronic versions of the same concept followed.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Modern systems use the comparison of phase or doppler techniques which are generally simpler to automate.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Early British radar sets were referred to as RDF, which is often stated was a deception.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In fact, the Chain Home systems used large RDF receivers to determine directions.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Later radar systems generally used a single antenna for broadcast and reception, and determined direction from the direction the antenna was facing.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The earliest experiments in RDF were carried out in 1888 when Heinrich Hertz discovered the directionality of an open loop of wire used as an antenna.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] When the antenna was aligned so it pointed at the signal it produced maximum gain, and produced zero signal when face on.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This meant there was always an ambiguity in the location of the signal: it would produce the same output if the signal was in front or back of the antenna.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Later experimenters also used dipole antennas, which worked in the opposite sense, reaching maximum gain at right angles and zero when aligned.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] RDF systems using mechanically swung loop or dipole antennas were common by the turn of the 20th century.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Prominent examples were patented by John Stone Stone in 1902 (U.S.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Patent 771,819), among many other examples.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By the early 1900s, many experimenters were looking for ways to use this concept for locating the position of a transmitter.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Early radio systems generally used medium wave and longwave signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Longwave in particular had good long-distance transmission characteristics due to their limited interaction with the ground, and thereby provided excellent great circle route ground wave propagation that pointed directly to the transmitter.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Methods of performing RDF on longwave signals was a major area of research during the 1900s and 1910s.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Antennas are generally sensitive to signals only when they have a length that is a significant portion of the wavelength, or larger.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Most antennas are at least 1⁄4 of the wavelength, more commonly 1⁄2 – the half-wave dipole is a very common design.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For longwave use, this resulted in loop antennas tens of feet on a side, often with more than one loop connected together to improve the signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Another solution to this problem was developed by the Marconi company in 1905.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This consisted of a number of horizontal wires or rods arranged to point outward from a common center point.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A movable switch could connect opposite pairs of these wires to form a dipole, and by rotating the switch the operator could hunt for the strongest signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The US Navy overcame this problem, to a point, by mounting antennas on ships and sailing in circles.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Such systems were unwieldily and impractical for many uses.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A key improvement in the RDF concept was introduced by Ettore Bellini and Alessandro Tosi in 1909 (U.S.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Their system used two such antennas, typically triangular loops, arranged at right angles.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The signals from the antennas were sent into coils wrapped around a wooden frame about the size of a drink can, where the signals were re-created in the area between the coils.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A separate loop antenna located in this area could then be used to hunt for the direction, without moving the main antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This made RDF so much more practical that it was soon being used for navigation on a wide scale, often as the first form of aerial navigation available, with ground stations homing in on the aircraft's radio set.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Bellini–Tosi direction finders were widespread from the 1920s into the 1950s.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Early RDF systems were useful largely for long wave signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These signals are able to travel very long distances, which made them useful for long-range navigation.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However, when the same technique was being applied to higher frequencies, unexpected difficulties arose due to the reflection of high frequency signals from the ionosphere.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The RDF station might now receive the same signal from two or more locations, especially during the day, which caused serious problems trying to determine the location.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This led to the 1919 introduction of the Adcock antenna (UK Patent 130,490), which consisted of four separate monopole antennas instead of two loops, eliminating the horizontal components and thus filtering out the sky waves being reflected down from the ionosphere.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Adcock antennas were widely used with Bellini–Tosi detectors from the 1920s on.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The US Army Air Corps in 1931 tested a primitive radio compass that used commercial stations as the beacon.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A major improvement in the RDF technique was introduced by Robert Watson-Watt as part of his experiments to locate lightning strikes as a method to indicate the direction of thunderstorms for sailors and airmen.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] He had long worked with conventional RDF systems, but these were difficult to use with the fleeting signals from the lightning.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] He had early on suggested the use of an oscilloscope to display these near instantly, but was unable to find one while working at the Met Office.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] When the office was moved, his new location at a radio research station provided him with both an Adcock antenna and a suitable oscilloscope, and he presented his new system in 1926.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In spite of the system being presented publicly, and its measurements widely reported in the UK, its impact on the art of RDF seems to be strangely subdued.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Development was limited until the mid-1930s, when the various British forces began widespread development and deployment of these "high-frequency direction finding", or "huff-duff" systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] To avoid RDF, the Germans had developed a method of broadcasting short messages under 30 seconds, less than the 60 seconds that a trained Bellini-Tosi operator would need to determine the direction.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However, this was useless against huff-duff systems, which located the signal with reasonable accuracy in seconds.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The Germans did not become aware of this problem until the middle of the war, and did not take any serious steps to address it until 1944.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By that time huff-duff had helped in about one-quarter of all successful attacks on the U-boat fleet.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Several developments in electronics during and after the Second World War led to greatly improved methods of comparing the phase of signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In addition, the phase-locked loop (PLL) allowed for easy tuning in of signals, which would not drift.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Improved vacuum tubes and the introduction of the transistor allowed much higher frequencies to be used economically, which led to widespread use of VHF and UHF signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] All of these changes led to new methods of RDF, and its much more widespread use.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In particular, the ability to compare the phase of signals led to phase-comparison RDF, which is perhaps the most widely used technique today.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In this system the loop antenna is replaced with a single square-shaped ferrite core, with loops wound around two perpendicular sides.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Signals from the loops are sent into a phase comparison circuit, whose output phase directly indicates the direction of the signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By sending this to any manner of display, and locking the signal using PLL, the direction to the broadcaster can be continuously displayed.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Operation consists solely of tuning in the station, and is so automatic that these systems are normally referred to as automatic direction finder.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Other systems have been developed where more accuracy is required.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Pseudo-doppler radio direction finder systems use a series of small dipole antennas arranged in a ring and use electronic switching to rapidly select dipoles to feed into the receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The resulting signal is processed and produces an audio tone.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The phase of that audio tone, compared to the antenna rotation, depends on the direction of the signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Doppler RDF systems have widely replaced the huff-duff system for location of fleeting signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The various procedures for radio direction finding to determine position at sea are no longer part of the maritime safety system GMDSS, which has been in force since 1999.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The striking cross frame antenna with attached auxiliary antenna can only be found on the signal masts of some older ships because they do not interfere there and dismantling would be too expensive.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Modern positioning methods such as GPS, DGPS, radar and the now-outdated Loran C have radio direction finding methods that are imprecise for today's needs.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Radio direction finding networks also no longer exist.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However rescue vessels, such as RNLI lifeboats in the UK, and Search and Rescue helicopters have direction finding receivers for marine VHF signals and the 121.5 MHz homing signals incorporated in EPIRB and PLB beacons, although modern GPS-EPIRBS and AIS beacons are slowly making these redundant.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A **radio direction finder** (**RDF**) is a device for finding the direction, or *bearing*, to a radio source.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The act of measuring the direction is known as **radio direction finding** or sometimes simply **direction finding** (**DF**).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Using two or more measurements from different locations, the location of an unknown transmitter can be determined; alternately, using two or more measurements of known transmitters, the location of a vehicle can be determined.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] RDF is widely used as a radio navigation system, especially with boats and aircraft.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] RDF systems can be used with any radio source, although the size of the receiver antennas are a function of the wavelength of the signal; very long wavelengths (low frequencies) require very large antennas, and are generally used only on ground-based systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These wavelengths are nevertheless very useful for marine navigation as they can travel very long distances and "over the horizon", which is valuable for ships when the line-of-sight may be only a few tens of kilometres.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For aircraft, where the horizon at altitude may extend to hundreds of kilometres, higher frequencies can be used, allowing much smaller antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] An automatic direction finder, often capable of being tuned to commercial AM radio transmitters, is a feature of almost all modern aircraft.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For the military, RDF systems are a key component of signals intelligence systems and methodologies.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The ability to locate the position of an enemy transmitter has been invaluable since World War I, and it played a key role in World War II's Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Modern systems often use phased array antennas to allow rapid beam forming for highly accurate results.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These are generally integrated into a wider electronic warfare suite.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Several distinct generations of RDF systems have been used over time, following new developments in electronics.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Early systems used mechanically rotated antennas that compared signal strengths from different directions, and several electronic versions of the same concept followed.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Modern pseudo-Doppler direction finder systems consist of a number of small antennas fixed to a circular card, with all of the processing performed by software.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Early British radar sets were also referred to as RDF, which was a deception tactic.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However, the terminology was not inaccurate; the Chain Home systems used separate omnidirectional broadcasters and large RDF receivers to determine the location of the targets.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In one type of direction finding, a directional antenna is used which is more sensitive in certain directions than in others.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Many antenna designs exhibit this property.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For example, a Yagi antenna has quite pronounced directionality, so the source of a transmission can be determined by pointing it in the direction where the maximum signal level is obtained.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Since the directional characteristics can be very broad, large antennas may be used to improve precision, or null techniques used to improve angular resolution.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A simple form of directional antenna is the loop aerial.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This consists of an open loop of wire on an insulating frame, or a metal ring that forms the antenna's loop element itself; often the diameter of the loop is a tenth of a wavelength or smaller at the target frequency.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Such an antenna will be *least* sensitive to signals that are perpendicular to its face and *most* responsive to those arriving edge-on.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This is caused by the phase of the received signal: The difference in electrical phase along the rim of the loop at any instant causes a difference in the voltages induced on either side of the loop.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Turning the plane of the loop to "face" the signal so that the arriving phases are identical around the entire rim will not induce any current flow in the loop.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] So simply turning the antenna to produce a *minimum* in the desired signal will establish two possible directions (front and back) from which the radio waves could be arriving.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Since the null direction gives a clearer indication of the signal direction – the null is "sharper" than the max – with loop aerial the null direction is used to locate a signal source.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A "sense antenna" is used to resolve the two direction possibilities; the sense aerial is a non-directional antenna configured to have the same sensitivity as the loop aerial.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By adding the steady signal from the sense aerial to the alternating signal from the loop signal as it rotates, there is now only one position as the loop rotates 360° at which there is zero current.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This acts as a phase reference point, allowing the correct null point to be identified, removing the 180° ambiguity.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A dipole antenna exhibits similar properties, as a small loop, although its null direction is not as "sharp".
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The Yagi-Uda antenna is familiar as the common VHF or UHF television aerial.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A Yagi antenna uses multiple dipole elements, which include "reflector" and "director" dipole elements.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The "reflector" is the longest dipole element and blocks nearly all the signal coming from behind it, hence a Yagi has no front vs. back directional ambiguity: The maximum signal only occurs when the narrowest end of the Yagi is aimed in the direction from which the radio waves are arriving.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] With a sufficient number of shorter "director" elements, a Yagi's maximum direction can be made to approach the sharpness of a small loop's null.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For much higher frequencies still, such as millimeter waves and microwaves, parabolic antennas or "dish" antennas can be used.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Dish antennas are highly directional, with the parabolic shape directing received signals from a very narrow angle into a small receiving element mounted at the focus of the parabola.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] More sophisticated techniques such as phased arrays are generally used for highly accurate direction finding systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The modern systems are called goniometers by analogy to WW II directional circuits used to measure direction by comparing the differences in two or more matched reference antennas' received signals, used in old signals intelligence (SIGINT).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A modern helicopter-mounted direction finding system was designed by ESL Incorporated for the U.S.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Time difference of arrival techniques compare the arrival time of a radio wave at two or more different antennas and deduce the direction of arrival from this timing information.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This method can use mechanically simple non-moving omnidirectional antenna elements fed into a multiple channel receiver system.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] One form of radio direction finding works by comparing the signal strength of a directional antenna pointing in different directions.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] At first, this system was used by land and marine-based radio operators, using a simple rotatable loop antenna linked to a degree indicator.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This system was later adopted for both ships and aircraft, and was widely used in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] On pre-World War II aircraft, RDF antennas are easy to identify as the circular loops mounted above or below the fuselage.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Later loop antenna designs were enclosed in an aerodynamic, teardrop-shaped fairing.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In ships and small boats, RDF receivers first employed large metal loop antennas, similar to aircraft, but usually mounted atop a portable battery-powered receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This null was symmetrical, and thus identified both the correct degree heading marked on the radio's compass rose as well as its 180-degree opposite.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] While this information provided a baseline from the station to the ship or aircraft, the navigator still needed to know beforehand if he was to the east or west of the station in order to avoid plotting a course 180-degrees in the wrong direction.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By taking bearings to two or more broadcast stations and plotting the intersecting bearings, the navigator could locate the relative position of his ship or aircraft.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Later, RDF sets were equipped with rotatable ferrite loopstick antennas, which made the sets more portable and less bulky.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Some were later partially automated by means of a motorized antenna (ADF).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A key breakthrough was the introduction of a secondary vertical whip or 'sense' antenna that substantiated the correct bearing and allowed the navigator to avoid plotting a bearing 180 degrees opposite the actual heading.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Navy RDF model SE 995 which used a sense antenna was in use during World War I.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] After World War II, there were many small and large firms making direction finding equipment for mariners, including Apelco, Aqua Guide, Bendix, Gladding (and its marine division, Pearce-Simpson), Ray Jefferson, Raytheon, and Sperry.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By the 1960s, many of these radios were actually made by Japanese electronics manufacturers, such as Panasonic, Fuji Onkyo, and Koden Electronics Co., Ltd.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In aircraft equipment, Bendix and Sperry-Rand were two of the larger manufacturers of RDF radios and navigation instruments.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Single-channel DF uses a multi-antenna array with a single channel radio receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This approach to DF offers some advantages and drawbacks.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Since it only uses one receiver, mobility and lower power consumption are benefits.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Without the ability to look at each antenna simultaneously (which would be the case if one were to use multiple receivers, also known as N-channel DF) more complex operations need to occur at the antenna in order to present the signal to the receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The two main categories that a single channel DF algorithm falls into are *amplitude comparison* and *phase comparison*.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Some algorithms can be hybrids of the two.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The pseudo-doppler technique is a phase based DF method that produces a bearing estimate on the received signal by measuring the doppler shift induced on the signal by sampling around the elements of a circular array.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The original method used a single antenna that physically moved in a circle but the modern approach uses a multi-antenna circular array with each antenna sampled in succession.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The Watson-Watt technique uses two antenna pairs to perform an amplitude comparison on the incoming signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The popular Watson-Watt method uses an array of two orthogonal coils (magnetic dipoles) in the horizontal plane, often completed with an omnidirectional vertically polarized electric dipole to resolve 180° ambiguities.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The Adcock antenna array uses a pair of monopole or dipole antennas that takes the vector difference of the received signal at each antenna so that there is only one output from each pair of antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Two of these pairs are co-located but perpendicularly oriented to produce what can be referred to as the N–S (North-South) and E–W (East-West) signals that will then be passed to the receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In the receiver, the bearing angle can then be computed by taking the arctangent of the ratio of the N–S to E–W signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The basic principle of the correlative interferometer consists in comparing the measured phase differences with the phase differences obtained for a DF antenna system of known configuration at a known wave angle (reference data set).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For this, at least three antenna elements (with omnidirectional reception characteristics) must form a non-collinear basis.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The comparison is made for different azimuth and elevation values of the reference data set.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The bearing result is obtained from a correlative and stochastic evaluation for which the correlation coefficient is at a maximum.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] If the direction finding antenna elements have a directional antenna pattern, then the amplitude may be included in the comparison.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Typically, the correlative interferometer DF system consists of more than five antenna elements.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These are scanned one after the other via a specific switching matrix.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In a multi-channel DF system n antenna elements are combined with m receiver channels to improve the DF-system performance.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Similar beacons located in coastal areas are also used for maritime radio navigation, as almost every ship was equipped with a direction finder (Appleyard 1988).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Very few maritime radio navigation beacons remain active today (2008) as ships have abandoned navigation via RDF in favor of GPS navigation.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In the United Kingdom a radio direction finding service is available on 121.5 MHz and 243.0 MHz to aircraft pilots who are in distress or are experiencing difficulties.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The service is based on a number of radio DF units located at civil and military airports and certain HM Coastguard stations.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These stations can obtain a "fix" of the aircraft and transmit it by radio to the pilot.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Radio transmitters for air and sea navigation are known as *beacons* and are the radio equivalent to a lighthouse.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The transmitter sends a Morse Code transmission on a Long wave (150 – 400 kHz) or Medium wave (520 – 1720 kHz) frequency incorporating the station's identifier that is used to confirm the station and its operational status.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Since these radio signals are broadcast in all directions (omnidirectional) during the day, the signal itself does not include direction information, and these beacons are therefore referred to as non-directional beacons, or **NDBs**.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] As the commercial medium wave broadcast band lies within the frequency capability of most RDF units, these stations and their transmitters can also be used for navigational fixes.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] While these commercial radio stations can be useful due to their high power and location near major cities, there may be several miles between the location of the station and its transmitter, which can reduce the accuracy of the 'fix' when approaching the broadcast city.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A second factor is that some AM radio stations are omnidirectional during the day, and switch to a reduced power, directional signal at night.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] RDF was once the primary form of aircraft and marine navigation.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Strings of beacons formed "airways" from airport to airport, while marine NDBs and commercial AM broadcast stations provided navigational assistance to small watercraft approaching a landfall.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In the United States, commercial AM radio stations were required to broadcast their station identifier once per hour for use by pilots and mariners as an aid to navigation.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In the 1950s, aviation NDBs were augmented by the VOR system, in which the direction to the beacon can be extracted from the signal itself, hence the distinction with non-directional beacons.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Use of marine NDBs was largely supplanted in North America by the development of LORAN in the 1970s.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Today many NDBs have been decommissioned in favor of faster and far more accurate GPS navigational systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However the low cost of ADF and RDF systems, and the continued existence of AM broadcast stations (as well as navigational beacons in countries outside North America) has allowed these devices to continue to function, primarily for use in small boats, as an adjunct or backup to GPS.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In World War II considerable effort was expended on identifying secret transmitters in the United Kingdom (UK) by direction finding.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The work was undertaken by the Radio Security Service (RSS also MI8).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Initially three U Adcock HF DF stations were set up in 1939 by the General Post Office.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] With the declaration of war, MI5 and RSS developed this into a larger network.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] One of the problems with providing coverage of an area the size of the UK was installing sufficient DF stations to cover the entire area to receive skywave signals reflected back from the ionised layers in the upper atmosphere.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Even with the expanded network, some areas were not adequately covered and for this reason up to 1700 voluntary interceptors (radio amateurs) were recruited to detect illicit transmissions by ground wave.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In addition to the fixed stations, RSS ran a fleet of mobile DF vehicles around the UK.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] If a transmitter was identified by the fixed DF stations or voluntary interceptors, the mobile units were sent to the area to home in on the source.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The mobile units were HF Adcock systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By 1941 only a couple of illicit transmitters had been identified in the UK; these were German agents that had been "turned" and were transmitting under MI5 control.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Many illicit transmissions had been logged emanating from German agents in occupied and neutral countries in Europe.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The traffic became a valuable source of intelligence, so the control of RSS was subsequently passed to MI6 who were responsible for secret intelligence originating from outside the UK.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The direction finding and interception operation increased in volume and importance until 1945.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The HF Adcock stations consisted of four 10 m vertical antennas surrounding a small wooden operators hut containing a receiver and a radio-goniometer which was adjusted to obtain the bearing.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] MF stations were also used which used four guyed 30 m lattice tower antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In 1941, RSS began experimenting with spaced loop direction finders, developed by the Marconi company and the UK National Physical Laboratories.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These consisted of two parallel loops 1 to 2 m square on the ends of a rotatable 3 to 8 m beam.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The angle of the beam was combined with results from a radiogoniometer to provide a bearing.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The bearing obtained was considerably sharper than that obtained with the U Adcock system, but there were ambiguities which prevented the installation of 7 proposed S.L DF systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The operator of an SL system was in a metal underground tank below the antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Seven underground tanks were installed, but only two SL systems were installed at Wymondham, Norfolk and Weaverthorp in Yorkshire.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Problems were encountered resulting in the remaining five underground tanks being fitted with Adcock systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The rotating SL antenna was turned by hand which meant successive measurements were a lot slower than turning the dial of a goniometer.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Another experimental spaced loop station was built near Aberdeen in 1942 for the Air Ministry with a semi-underground concrete bunker.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This, too, was abandoned because of operating difficulties.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] By 1944, a mobile version of the spaced loop had been developed and was used by RSS in France following the D-Day invasion of Normandy.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The US military used a shore based version of the spaced loop DF in World War II called "DAB".
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The loops were placed at the ends of a beam, all of which was located inside a wooden hut with the electronics in a large cabinet with cathode-ray-tube display at the centre of the beam and everything being supported on a central axis.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The beam was rotated manually by the operator.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The Royal Navy introduced a variation on the shore based HF DF stations in 1944 to track U-boats in the North Atlantic.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] They built groups of five DF stations, so that bearings from individual stations in the group could be combined and a mean taken.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Four such groups were built in Britain at Ford End, Essex; Goonhavern, Cornwall; and Anstruther and Bowermadden in the Scottish Highlands.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Groups were also built in Iceland, Nova Scotia, and Jamaica.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The anticipated improvements were not realised but later statistical work improved the system and the Goonhavern and Ford End groups continued to be used during the Cold War.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The Royal Navy also deployed direction finding equipment on ships tasked to anti-submarine warfare in order to try to locate German submarines, e.g.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Captain class frigates were fitted with a medium frequency direction finding antenna (MF/DF) (the antenna was fitted in front of the bridge) and high frequency direction finding (HF/DF, "Huffduff") Type FH 4 antenna (the antenna was fitted on top of the mainmast).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A comprehensive reference on World War II wireless direction finding was written by Roland Keen, who was head of the engineering department of RSS at Hanslope Park.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The DF systems mentioned here are described in detail in his 1947 book *Wireless Direction Finding*.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] At the end of World War II a number of RSS DF stations continued to operate into the Cold War under the control of GCHQ the British SIGINT organisation.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Most direction finding effort within the UK now (2009) is directed towards locating unauthorised "pirate" FM broadcast radio transmissions.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] A network of remotely operated VHF direction finders are used mainly located around the major cities.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The transmissions from mobile telephone handsets are also located by a form of direction finding using the comparative signal strength at the surrounding local "cell" receivers.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This technique is often offered as evidence in UK criminal prosecutions and, almost certainly, for SIGINT purposes.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Emergency position-indicating rescue beacons are widely deployed on civil aircraft and ships.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Historically emergency location transmitters only sent a tone signal and relied on direction finding by search aircraft to locate the beacon.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Modern emergency beacons transmit a unique identification signal that can include GPS location data that can aid in finding the exact location of the transmitter.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Avalanche transceivers operate on a standard 457 kHz, and are designed to help locate people and equipment buried by avalanches.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Since the power of the beacon is so low the directionality of the radio signal is dominated by small scale field effects and can be quite complicated to locate.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Location of radio-tagged animals by triangulation is a widely applied research technique for studying the movement of animals.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The technique was first used in the early 1960s, when radio transmitters and batteries became small enough to attach to wildlife, and is now widely deployed for a variety of wildlife studies.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Most tracking of wild animals that have been affixed with radio transmitter equipment is done by a field researcher using a handheld radio direction finding device.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] When the researcher wants to locate a particular animal, the location of the animal can be triangulated by determining the direction to the transmitter from several locations.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Phased arrays and other advanced antenna techniques are utilized to track launches of rocket systems and their resulting trajectories.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These systems can be used for defensive purposes and also to gain intelligence on operation of missiles belonging to other nations.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] These same techniques are used for detection and tracking of conventional aircraft.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Earth-based receivers can detect radio signals emanating from distant stars or regions of ionized gas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Receivers in radio telescopes can detect the general direction of such naturally occurring radio sources, sometimes correlating their location with objects visible with optical telescopes.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Accurate measurement of the arrival time of radio impulses by two radio telescopes at different places on Earth, or the same telescope at different times in Earth's orbit around the Sun, may also allow estimation of the distance to a radio object.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Events hosted by groups and organizations that involve the use of radio direction finding skills to locate transmitters at unknown locations have been popular since the end of World War II.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Many of these events were first promoted in order to practice the use of radio direction finding techniques for disaster response and civil defense purposes, or to practice locating the source of radio frequency interference.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The most popular form of the sport, worldwide, is known as amateur radio direction finding (ARDF).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] DF techniques for microwave frequencies were developed in the 1940s, in response to the growing numbers of transmitters operating at these higher frequencies.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This required the design of new antennas and receivers for the DF systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In Naval systems, the DF capability became part of the Electronic Support Measures suite (ESM), where the directional information obtained augments other signal identification processes.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In aircraft, a DF system provides additional information for the Radar Warning Receiver (RWR).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Over time, it became necessary to improve the performance of microwave DF systems in order to counter the evasive tactics being employed by some operators, such as low-probability-of-intercept radars and covert Data links.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Earlier in the century, vacuum tubes (thermionic valves) were used extensively in transmitters and receivers, but their high frequency performance was limited by transit time effects.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Even with special processes to reduce lead lengths, such as frame grid construction, as used in the EF50, and planar construction, very few tubes could operate above UHF.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Intensive research work was carried out in the 1930s in order to develop transmitting tubes specifically for the microwave band which included, in particular, the klystron the cavity magnetron and the travelling wave tube (TWT).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Following the successful development of these tubes, large scale production occurred in the following decade.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Microwave signals have short wavelengths, which results in greatly improved target resolution when compared to RF systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This permits better identification of multiple targets and, also, gives improved directional accuracy.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Also, the antennas are small so they can be assembled into compact arrays and, in addition, they can achieve well defined beam patterns which can provide the narrow beams with high gain favoured by radars and Data links.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Other advantages of the newly available microwave band were the absence of fading (often a problem in the Shortwave radio (SW) band) and great increase in signal spectrum, compared to the congested RF bands already in use.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In addition to being able to accommodate many more signals, the ability to use Spread spectrum and frequency hopping techniques now became possible.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Once microwave techniques had become established, there was rapid expansion into the band by both military and commercial users.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Antennas for DF have to meet different requirements from those for a radar or communication link, where an antenna with a narrow beam and high gain is usually an advantage.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However, when carrying out direction finding, the bearing of the source may be unknown, so antennas with wide beamwidths are usually chosen, even though they have lower antenna boresight gain.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In addition, the antennas are required to cover a wide band of frequencies.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The figure shows the normalized polar plot of a typical antenna gain characteristic, in the horizontal plane.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The half-power beamwidth of the main beam is 2 × Ψ0.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Preferably, when using amplitude comparison methods for direction finding, the main lobe should approximate to a Gaussian characteristic.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Although the figure also shows the presence of sidelobes, these are not a major concern when antennas are used in a DF array.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Typically, the boresight gain of an antenna is related to the beam width.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For a rectangular horn, ${\text{Gain}}\approx {\frac {30,\!000}{\mathrm {BW} _{h}\times \mathrm {BW} _{v}}}$ where BW*h* and BW*v* are the horizontal and vertical antenna beamwidths, respectively, in degrees.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Two antenna types, popular for DF, are cavity-backed spirals and horn antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Spiral antennas are capable of very wide bandwidths and have a nominal half-power beamwidth of about 70deg, making them very suitable for antenna arrays containing 4, 5 or 6 antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] For larger arrays, needing narrower beamwidths, horns may be used.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The bandwidths of horn antennas may be increased by using double-ridged waveguide feeds and by using horns with internal ridges.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Early microwave receivers were usually simple "crystal-video" receivers, which use a crystal detector followed by a video amplifier with a compressive characteristic to extend the dynamic range.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Such a receiver was wideband but not very sensitive.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However, this lack of sensitivity could be tolerated because of the "range advantage" enjoyed by the DF receiver (see below).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The klystron and TWT are linear devices and so, in principle, could be used as receiver preamplifiers.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However, the klystron was quite unsuitable as it was a narrow-band device and extremely noisy and the TWT, although potentially more suitable, has poor matching characteristics and large bulk, which made it unsuitable for multi-channel systems using a preamplifier per antenna.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] However, a system has been demonstrated, in which a single TWT preamplifier selectively selects signals from an antenna array.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Transistors suitable for microwave frequencies became available towards the end of the 1950s.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The first of these was the metal oxide semiconductor field effect transistor (MOSFET).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Others followed, for example, the metal-semiconductor field-effect transistor and the high electron mobility transistor (HEMT).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Initially, discrete transistors were embedded in stripline or microstrip circuits, but microwave integrated circuits followed.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] With these new devices, low-noise receiver preamplifiers became possible, which greatly increased the sensitivity, and hence the detection range, of DF systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The DF receiver enjoys a detection range advantage over that of the radar receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This is because the signal strength at the DF receiver, due to a radar transmission, is proportional to 1/*R*2 whereas that at the radar receiver from the reflected return is proportional to *σ*/*R*4, where R is the range and σ is the radar cross-section of the DF system.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] This results in the signal strength at the radar receiver being very much smaller than that at the DF receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Consequently, in spite of its poor sensitivity, a simple crystal-video DF receiver is, usually, able to detect the signal transmission from a radar at a greater range than that at which the Radar's own receiver is able to detect the presence of the DF system.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In practice, the advantage is reduced by the ratio of antenna gains (typically they are 36 dB and 10 dB for the Radar and ESM, respectively) and the use of Spread spectrum techniques, such as Chirp compression, by the Radar, to increase the processing gain of its receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] On the other hand, the DF system can regain some advantage by using sensitive, low-noise, receivers and by using Stealth practices to reduce its radar cross-section, as with Stealth aircraft and Stealth ships.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] The move to microwave frequencies meant a reappraisal of the requirements of a DF system.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Now, the receiver could no longer rely on a continuous signal stream on which to carry out measurements.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Radars with their narrow beams would only illuminate the antennas of the DF system infrequently.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Furthermore, some radars wishing to avoid detection (those of smugglers, hostile ships and missiles) would radiate their signals infrequently and often at low power.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] Such a system is referred to as a low-probability-of-intercept radar.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In other applications, such as microwave links, the transmitter's antenna may never point at the DF receiver at all, so reception is only possible by means of the signal leakage from antenna side lobes.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In addition, covert Data links may only radiate a high data rate sequence very occasionally.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p01] In general, in order to cater for modern circumstances, a broadband microwave DF system is required to have high sensitivity and have 360° coverage in order to have the ability to detect single pulses (often called amplitude monopulse) and achieve a high "Probability of Intercept" (PoI).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Amplitude comparison has been popular as a method for DF because systems are relatively simple to implement, have good sensitivity and, very importantly, a high probability of signal detection.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Typically, an array of four, or more, squinted directional antennas is used to give 360 degree coverage.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] DF by phase comparison methods can give better bearing accuracy, but the processing is more complex.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Systems using a single rotating dish antenna are more sensitive, small and relatively easy to implement, but have poor PoI.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Usually, the signal amplitudes in two adjacent channels of the array are compared, to obtain the bearing of an incoming wavefront but, sometimes, three adjacent channels are used to give improved accuracy.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Although the gains of the antennas and their amplifying chains have to be closely matched, careful design and construction and effective calibration procedures can compensate for shortfalls in the hardware.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Overall bearing accuracies of 2° to 10° (rms) have been reported using the method.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Two-channel DF, using two adjacent antennas of a circular array, is achieved by comparing the signal power of the largest signal with that of the second largest signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] The direction of an incoming signal, within the arc described by two antennas with a squint angle of Φ, may be obtained by comparing the relative powers of the signals received.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] When the signal is on the boresight of one of the antennas, the signal at the other antenna will be about 12 dB lower.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] When the signal direction is halfway between the two antennas, signal levels will be equal and approximately 3 dB lower than the boresight value.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] At other bearing angles, φ, some intermediate ratio of the signal levels will give the direction.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] To give 360° coverage, antennas of a circular array are chosen, in pairs, according to the signal levels received at each antenna.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] If there are N antennas in the array, at angular spacing (squint angle) Φ, then Φ = 2π/*N* radians (= 360/*N* degrees).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] This shows the linear relationship between the output level difference, expressed logarithmically, and the bearing angle φ.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Improvements in bearing accuracy may be achieved if amplitude data from a third antenna are included in the bearing processing.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] For three-channel DF, with three antennas squinted at angles Φ, the direction of the incoming signal is obtained by comparing the signal power of the channel containing the largest signal with the signal powers of the two adjacent channels, situated at each side of it.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] For the antennas in a circular array, three antennas are selected according to the signal levels received, with the largest signal present at the central channel.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] When the signal is on the boresight of Antenna 1 (*φ* = 0), the signal from the other two antennas will equal and about 12 dB lower.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] When the signal direction is halfway between two antennas (*φ* = 30°), their signal levels will be equal and approximately 3 dB lower than the boresight value, with the third signal now about 24 dB lower.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] At other bearing angles, φ, some intermediate ratios of the signal levels will give the direction.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] where GT is the overall gain of each channel, including antenna boresight gain, and is assumed to be the same in all three channels.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] As before, in these equations, angles are in radians, Φ = 360/*N* degrees = 2π/*N* radians and *A* = –ln(0.5).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] The difference values here are in nepers but could be in decibels.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] The bearing value, obtained using this equation, is independent of the antenna beamwidth (= 2Ψ0), so this value does not have to be known for accurate bearing results to be obtained.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Also, there is a smoothing affect, for bearing values near to the boresight of the middle antenna, so there is no discontinuity in bearing values there, as an incoming signals moves from left to right (or vice versa) through boresight, as can occur with 2-channel processing.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Many of the causes of bearing error, such as mechanical imperfections in the antenna structure, poor gain matching of receiver gains, or non-ideal antenna gain patterns may be compensated by calibration procedures and corrective look-up tables, but thermal noise will always be a degrading factor.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] As all systems generate thermal noise then, when the level of the incoming signal is low, the signal-to-noise ratios in the receiver channels will be poor, and the accuracy of the bearing prediction will suffer.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] for a signal at crossover, but where SNR0 is the signal-to-noise ratio that would apply at boresight.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] To obtain more precise predictions at a given bearing, the actual S:N ratios of the signals of interest are used.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] (The results may be derived assuming that noise induced errors are approximated by relating differentials to uncorrelated noise).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] For adjacent processing using, say, Channel 1 and Channel 2, the bearing uncertainty (angle noise), Δ*φ* (rms), is given below.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] In these results, square-law detection is assumed and the SNR figures are for signals at video (baseband), for the bearing angle φ.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] where SNR1 and SNR2 are the video (base-band) signal-to-noise values for the channels for Antenna 1 and Antenna 2, when square-law detection is used.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] where SNR1, SNR2 and SNR3 are the video signal-to-noise values for Channel 1, Channel 2, and Channel 3 respectively, for the bearing angle φ.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] A schematic of a possible DF system, employing six antennas, is shown in the figure.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] The signals received by the antennas are first amplified by a low-noise preamplifier before detection by detector-log-video-amplifiers (DLVAs).
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] The signal levels from the DLVAs are compared to determine the angle of arrival.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] By considering the signal levels on a logarithmic scale, as provided by the DLVAs, a large dynamic range is achieved and, in addition, the direction finding calculations are simplified when the main lobes of antenna patterns have a Gaussian characteristic, as shown earlier.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] A necessary part of the DF analysis is to identify the channel which contains the largest signal and this is achieved by means of a fast comparator circuit.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] In addition to the DF process, other properties of the signal may be investigated, such as pulse duration, frequency, pulse repetition frequency (PRF) and modulation characteristics.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] The comparator operation usually includes hysteresis, to avoid jitter in the selection process when the bearing of the incoming signal is such that two adjacent channels contain signals of similar amplitude.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Often, the wideband amplifiers are protected from local high power sources (as on a ship) by input limiters and/or filters.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Similarly the amplifiers might contain notch filters to remove known, but unwanted, signals which could impairs the system's ability to process weaker signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/direction-finding-p02] Some of these issues are covered in RF chain.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] An **electronic countermeasure** (**ECM**) is an electrical or electronic device designed to trick or deceive radar, sonar, or other detection systems, like infrared (IR) or lasers.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] It may be used offensively and defensively to deny targeting information to an enemy.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The system may make many separate targets appear to the enemy, or make the real target appear to disappear or move about randomly.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] It is used effectively to protect aircraft from guided missiles.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Most air forces use ECM to protect their aircraft from attack.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] It has also been deployed by military ships and recently on some advanced tanks to fool laser/IR guided missiles.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] It is frequently coupled with stealth advances, so the ECM systems have an easier job.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Offensive ECM often takes the form of jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Self-protecting (defensive) ECM includes blip enhancement and jamming missile terminal homers.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The first example of electronic countermeasures applied in combat occurred during the Russo-Japanese War.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] On July 13, 1904, Russian wireless telegraphy stations installed in the Port Arthur fortress and on board Russian light cruisers successfully interrupted wireless communication between Japanese battleships.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The spark-gap transmitters in the Russian stations generated senseless noise while the Japanese were making attempts to coordinate their efforts in the bombing of a Russian naval base.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] During World War I, Germany and the United Kingdom interfered with enemy communications along the western front, while the Royal Navy tried to intercept German naval radio transmissions.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] There were also efforts to send false radio signals, such as having shore stations send transmissions using ships' call signs and jamming enemy radio signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] On the other hand, there were also attempts by the Ottoman side to jam Allied wireless communications during the Gallipoli campaign.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] World War II ECM expanded to include dropping chaff (originally called Window), jamming and spoofing radar and navigation signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] German bomber aircraft navigated using radio signals transmitted from ground stations, which the British disrupted with spoofed signals in the Battle of the Beams.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] During the RAF's night attacks on Germany, the extent of electronic countermeasures was much expanded, and a specialised organisation, No.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] 100 Group RAF, was formed to counter the increasing German night fighter force and radar defences.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Cold War developments included anti-radiation missiles designed to home in on enemy radar transmitters.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] In the 2007 Operation Orchard Israeli attack on a suspected Syrian nuclear weapons site, the Israel Air Force used electronic warfare to take control of Syrian airspace before the attack.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Israeli electronic warfare (EW) systems took over Syria's air defense systems, feeding them a false sky-picture.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] At the same time, Israel Air Force jets crossed much of Syria, bombed their targets and returned.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Basic radar ECM strategies are (1) radar interference, (2) target modifications, and (3) changing the electrical properties of air.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Interference techniques include jamming and deception.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Jamming is accomplished by a friendly platform transmitting signals on the radar frequency to produce a noise level sufficient to hide echoes.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The jammer's continuous transmissions will provide a clear direction to the enemy radar, but no range information.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Deception may use a transponder to mimic the radar echo with a delay to indicate incorrect range.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Transponders may alternatively increase return echo strength to make a small decoy appear to be a larger target.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Target modifications include radar absorbing coatings and modifications of the surface shape to either "stealth" a high-value target or enhance reflections from a decoy.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Dispersal of small aluminium strips called chaff is a common method of changing the electromagnetic properties of air to provide confusing radar echoes.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Radio or communications jamming is the deliberate transmission of radio signals that disrupt communications by decreasing the signal-to-noise ratio to the point where the target communications link is either degraded or denied service.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] ECM is practiced by nearly all modern military units—land, sea or air.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Aircraft, however, are the primary weapons in the ECM battle because they can "see" a larger patch of earth than a sea or land-based unit.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] When employed effectively, ECM can keep aircraft from being tracked by search radars or targeted by surface-to-air missiles or air-to-air missiles.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] An aircraft ECM can take the form of an attachable underwing pod or be embedded in the airframe.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Fighter planes using a conventional electronically scanned antenna mount dedicated jamming pods instead, or, in the case of the US, German, and Italian air forces, may rely on electronic warfare aircraft to carry them.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The Next Generation Jammer is being developed to replace the current AN/ALQ-99 carried on the E/A-18G electronic warfare plane.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Planned for adoption around 2020, it will use a small AESA antenna divided into quadrants for all-around coverage and retain the capability of highly directional jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] DARPA's Precision Electronic Warfare (PREW) project aims to develop a low-cost system capable of synchronizing several simple airborne jamming pods with enough precision to replicate the directionality of an electronically scanned antenna, avoiding collateral jamming of non-targeted receivers.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Selex ES has already developed an expendable active decoy that uses DRFM technology to jam RF-based threats.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] (merged into Leonardo, the new name of Finmeccanica since 2017).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The system, named BriteCloud, is self-contained within a small canister similar to a standard flare cartridge.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The 55 mm format of the system has undergone flight trials with the Gripen aircraft, and the development of a 218 variant is at an advanced stage.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The ULQ-6 deception transmitter was one of the earlier shipboard ECM installations.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The Raytheon SLQ-32 shipboard ECM package came in three versions, providing warning, identification and bearing information about radar-guided cruise missiles.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The SLQ-32 V3 included quick reaction electronic countermeasures for cruisers, large amphibious ships, auxiliaries, and the RBOC (Rapid Blooming Off-board Chaff) launchers found on most surface ships.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] The BLR-14 Submarine Acoustic Warfare System (or SAWS) provides an integrated receiver, processor, display, and countermeasures launch system for submarines.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Infrared homing systems can be decoyed with flares and other infrared countermeasures.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Acoustic homing and detection systems used for ships are also susceptible to countermeasures.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] United States warships use Masker and PRAIRIE (propeller AIR Ingestion and Emission) systems to create small air bubbles around a ship's hull and wake to reduce sound transmission.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Surface ships tow noisemakers like the AN/SLQ-25 Nixie to decoy homing torpedoes.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Submarines can deploy similar acoustic device countermeasures (or ADCs) from a 3-inch (75-mm) signal launching tube.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] United States ballistic missile submarines could deploy the Mark 70 MOSS (Mobile submarine simulator) decoy from torpedo tubes to simulate a full size submarine.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-countermeasure] Most navies additionally equip ships with decoy launchers.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] In military telecommunications, **electronic support** (**ES**) or **electronic support measures** (**ESM**) gather intelligence through passive "listening" to electromagnetic radiations of military interest.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] Thus, electronic support provides a source of information required for decisions involving electronic protection (EP), electronic attack (EA), avoidance, targeting, and other tactical employment of forces.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] Electronic support data can be used to produce signals intelligence (SIGINT), communications intelligence (COMINT) and electronics intelligence (ELINT).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] Electronic support measures can provide (1) initial detection or knowledge of foreign systems, (2) a library of technical and operational data on foreign systems, and (3) tactical combat information utilizing that library.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] ESM collection platforms can remain electronically silent and detect and analyze RADAR transmissions beyond the RADAR detection range because of the greater power of the transmitted electromagnetic pulse with respect to a reflected echo of that pulse.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] United States airborne ESM receivers are designated in the AN/ALR series.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] The frequency spectrum of interest ranges from 30 MHz to 50 GHz.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare-support-measures] Multiple receivers are typically required for surveillance of the entire spectrum, but tactical receivers may be functional within a specific signal strength threshold of a smaller frequency range.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Military operations are executed in an information environment increasingly complicated by the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The electromagnetic spectrum portion of the information environment is referred to as the electromagnetic environment (EME).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The recognized need for military forces to have unimpeded access to and use of the electromagnetic environment creates vulnerabilities and opportunities for electronic warfare in support of military operations.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Within the information operations construct, EW is an element of information warfare; more specifically, it is an element of offensive and defensive counterinformation.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] NATO has a different and arguably more encompassing and comprehensive approach to EW.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] A military committee conceptual document from 2007, *MCM_0142 Nov 2007 Military Committee Transformation Concept for Future NATO Electronic Warfare*, recognised the EME as an operational maneuver space and warfighting environment/domain.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In NATO, EW is considered to be warfare in the EME.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] NATO has adopted simplified language which parallels those used in other warfighting environments like maritime, land, and air/space.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] For example, an electronic attack (EA) is offensive use of EM energy, electronic defense (ED), and electronic surveillance (ES).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The use of the traditional NATO EW terms, electronic countermeasures (ECM), electronic protective measures (EPM), and electronic support measures (ESM) has been retained as they contribute to and support electronic attack (EA), electronic defense (ED) and electronic surveillance (ES).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Besides EW, other EM operations include intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition and reconnaissance (ISTAR), and signals intelligence (SIGINT).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Subsequently, NATO has issued EW policy and doctrine and is addressing the other NATO defense lines of development.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Primary EW activities have been developed over time to exploit the opportunities and vulnerabilities that are inherent in the physics of EM energy.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Electronic warfare consists of three major subdivisions: electronic attack (EA), electronic protection (EP), and electronic warfare support (ES).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In the case of electromagnetic energy, this action is most commonly referred to as "jamming" and can be performed on communications systems or radar systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In the case of anti-radiation weapons, this often includes missiles or bombs that can home in on a specific signal (radio or radar) and follow that path directly to impact, thus destroying the system broadcasting.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In November 2021, Israel Aerospace Industries announced a new electronic warfare system named Scorpius that can disrupt radar and communications from ships, UAVs, and missiles simultaneously and at varying distances.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] On 8 September 2024, Russian drones entered both Romanian and Latvian airspace.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Romania scrambled two F-16s to monitor one of the drones, which landed "in an uninhabited area" near Periprava, according to the Romanian Ministry of Defence.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The drone that entered Latvian airspace from Belarus crashed near Rezekne.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] This comes as the ISW noted increased success in Ukrainian Electronic Warfare against Russian drones that resulted in "several Russian Shahed drones (that) recently failed to reach their intended targets for unknown reasons." Two Kh-58s also reportedly failed to reach their targets.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The effectiveness of electronic protection (EP) level is the ability to counter an electronic attack (EA).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Flares are often used to distract infrared homing missiles into missing their target.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The use of flare rejection logic in the guidance (seeker head) of an infrared homing missile to counter an adversary's use of flares is an example of EP.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] While defensive EA actions (jamming) and EP (defeating jamming) both protect personnel, facilities, capabilities, and equipment, EP protects from the *effects* of EA (friendly and/or adversary).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Other examples of EP include spread spectrum technologies, the use of restricted frequency lists, emissions control (EMCON), and low observability (stealth) technology.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] An electronic warfare tactics range (EWTR) is a practice range that provides training for personnel operating in electronic warfare.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] There are two examples of such ranges in Europe: one at RAF Spadeadam in the northwest county of Cumbria, England, and the Multinational Aircrew Electronic Warfare Tactics Facility Polygone range on the border between Germany and France.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] EWTRs are equipped with ground-based equipment to simulate electronic warfare threats that aircrew might encounter on missions.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Other EW training and tactics ranges are available for ground and naval forces as well.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Antifragile EW is a step beyond standard EP, occurring when a communications link being jammed actually increases in capability as a result of a jamming attack, although this is only possible under certain circumstances such as reactive forms of jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Electronic warfare support (ES) is a subdivision of EW involving actions taken by an operational commander or operator to detect, intercept, identify, locate, and/or localize sources of intended and unintended radiated electromagnetic (EM) energy.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] These Electronic Support Measures (ESM) aim to enable immediate threat recognition focuses on serving military service needs even in the most tactical, rugged, and extreme environments.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] This is often referred to as simply reconnaissance, although today, more common terms are intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance (ISR) or intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition, and reconnaissance (ISTAR).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The purpose is to provide immediate recognition, prioritization, and targeting of threats to battlefield commanders.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Signals intelligence (SIGINT), a discipline overlapping with ES, is the related process of analyzing and identifying intercepted transmissions from sources such as radio communication, mobile phones, radar, or microwave communication.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] SIGINT is broken into two categories: electronic intelligence (ELINT) and communications intelligence (COMINT).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Analysis parameters measured in signals of these categories can include frequency, bandwidth, modulation, and polarization.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The distinction between SIGINT and ES is determined by the controller of the collection assets, the information provided, and the intended purpose of the information.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Electronic warfare support is conducted by assets under the operational control of a commander to provide tactical information, specifically threat prioritization, recognition, location, targeting, and avoidance.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] However, the same assets and resources that are tasked with ES can simultaneously collect information that meets the collection requirements for more strategic intelligence.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The earliest documented use of EW was during the Second Boer War of 1899–1902.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The British Army, when trying to relieve Ladysmith, under siege by the Boers, used a searchlight to "bounce" Morse code signals off the clouds.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The Boers immediately spotted this and used one of their own searchlights in an attempt to jam the British signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] This was graphically described by Winston Churchill in his book *London to Ladysmith via Pretoria*.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The very first military attempts at radio jamming were reportedly made during exercises by the Royal Navy in 1902, and by the US Navy in 1903.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Nonetheless, the first documented radio jamming was reportedly a civil one.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The first recorded wireless interception was performed by HMS *Diana* in the Suez Canal in 1904, which was capable of recording Russian telecommunications.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The first recorded attempt at wartime jamming happened during the Russo-Japanese War of 1904-1905.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] On 8 March 1904, as the Japanese Navy was attempting a long-distance bombardment of Port Arthur using cruisers with a "spotter" destroyer that radioed them ballistic corrections.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] A Russian radio operator, hearing the presence of communications, used his Spark-gap transmitter to attempt to drown out the communications, allegedly leading the Japanese to promptly retreat without having achieved their objectives.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] During May 1905, Russian Admiral Zinovy Rozhestvensky was attempting to cross the Tsushima Strait to rejoin Vladivostok after having repaired some of his ships in Madagascar.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The Russian Navy was spotted by the Japanese armed Merchantman *Shinano Maru*.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The captain of the Russian warship *Ural* requested permission to disrupt the Japanese communications link by attempting to transmit a stronger radio signal, hoping to distort the Japanese signal at the receiving end.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Rozhestvensky refused the advice and denied the *Ural* permission to radio jam the enemy, as it could have signaled the position of the Russian Fleet.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] He also refused to send scouting ships for the same reason.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] While it is doubtful that jamming the Japanese would have changed the outcome of the Battle of Tsushima that ensued, this hints at the fact that radio jamming was already a standard procedure by this time - as was wireless communication interception.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Chaff was also introduced during WWII to confuse and defeat tracking radar systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] As battlefield communication and radar technology improved, so did electronic warfare, which played a major role in several military operations during the Vietnam War.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Aircraft on bombing runs and air-to-air missions often relied on EW to survive the battle, although many were defeated by Vietnamese ECCM.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Electronic Warfare was used extensively during the Gulf War, primarily by USAF and USN electronic attack aircraft such as the EF-111A and EA-6B to disrupt Iraq's large and capable SAM and GCI network.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In 2007, an Israeli attack on a suspected Syrian nuclear site during Operation Outside the Box (or Operation Orchard) used electronic warfare systems to disrupt Syrian air defenses while Israeli jets crossed much of Syria, bombed their targets, and returned to Israel undeterred.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The target was a suspected nuclear reactor under construction near the Euphrates River, modeled after a North Korean reactor and supposedly financed with Iranian assistance.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Some reports say Israeli EW systems deactivated all of Syria's air defense systems for the entire period of the raid.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In December 2010, the Russian Army deployed their first land-based multifunctional electronic warfare system known as Borisoglebsk 2, developed by Sozvezdie.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Development of the system started in 2004 and evaluation testing successfully completed in December 2010.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The Borisoglebsk-2 uses four different types of jamming stations on a single system.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The Borisoglebsk-2 system is mounted on nine MT-LB armored vehicles and is intended to suppress mobile satellite communications and satellite-based navigation signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] This EW system is developed to conduct electronic reconnaissance and suppression of radio-frequency sources.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In August 2015, the Swedish newspaper *Svenska Dagbladet* said its initial usage caused concern within NATO.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] During the first two days of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Russian EW disrupted Ukraine's air defense radars and communications, severely disrupting Ukrainian ground-based air defense systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Russian jamming was so effective it interfered with their own communications, so efforts were scaled back.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] This led to Ukrainian SAMs regaining much of their effectiveness, which began inflicting significant losses on Russian aircraft by the start of March 2022.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Rapid Russian advances at the start of the war prevented EW troops from properly supporting the advancing troops, but by late March and April 2022, extensive jamming infrastructure had been deployed.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] EW complexes were set up in Donbas in concentrations of up to 10 complexes per 13 mi (21 km) of frontage.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Electronic suppression of GPS and radio signals caused heavy losses of Ukrainian UAVs, depriving them of intelligence and precise artillery fire spotting.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Small quadcopters had an average life expectancy of around three flights, and larger fixed-wing UAVs like the Bayraktar TB2 had a life expectancy of about six flights.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] By summer 2022, only some one-third of Ukrainian UAV missions could be said to have been successful, as EW had contributed to Ukraine losing 90% of the thousands of drones it had at the beginning of the invasion.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Russian EW capacity to disrupt GPS signals is credited with the reduction in the success of Ukrainian usage of HIMARS and JDAM bombs.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] The failure of GPS guidance forces these weapons, in particular JDAMS, to use inertial navigation system which reduces accuracy from around 5 metres (15 ft) down to around 27 metres (90 ft).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In April 2026, reports emerged that Ukrainian F-16 pilots were being instructed by the Royal Air Force to operate in GPS-denied environments.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Pilots were trained in low-altitude visual navigation and terrain-based orientation methods intended to compensate for degraded satellite navigation systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Ukraine was losing some 10,000 drones a month due to Russian electronic warfare, according to a 19 May 2023 report by the Royal United Services Institute.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] This was an average of 300 drones a day.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Russia has established EW posts about every 10 kilometres (6 mi) of the front, being some 6 kilometres (4 mi) back from the front line.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In October 2023, *The Economist* reported that electronic warfare was in widespread use on front lines to impair small battlefield UAV activity, with Russia installing video feedback and control jammers on high-value equipment like tanks and artillery.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] By 11 March 2024, Ukraine reported it had destroyed a Russian Palantin EW system in Zaporizhzhia Oblast, which "suppress satellite radio navigation along the entire line of contact and in most parts of Ukraine, replacing the satellite radio navigation field (spoofing)".
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] An estimated three Palantin systems have been hit (June 2022, February 2023, and March 2024).
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In addition to the Palantin, in Zaporizhzhia a Layer EW system was destroyed.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Originating from digital EW, and as a continuation of software based modulation and demodulation, cognitive electronic warfare or cognitive electromagnetic warfare (CEW), is the use of AI in electronic warfare systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] CEW is affecting all electronic warfare subdivisions, and can improve situation-assessment (SA) and ESM, through automatic detection and classification of new and unknown signals, signatures, and even RCS.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Cognitive electronic warfare systems can be used to collect ESM data and assist augmenting, updating, and broadcasting (over JTIDS), real time maps with electronic order of battle (EOB) and electronic identification (EID) data.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] As well as the ability to adapt in real time to changes in the electromagnetic spectrum, by using artificial intelligence algorithms to quickly generate optimal EA, or EP solutions.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] It can provide more comprehensive information to cryptologic technicians, by helping to select the jamming techniques that will be the most effective, and therefore provide faster and better ECM, or ECCM, decisions.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] CEW is part of the *Electromagnetic Spectrum Superiority Strategy* (ESSS), published in October 2020, according to Lieutenant Commander Brian P.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] DARPA has used CEW in some SIGINT studies with convolutional neural networks.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] In 2026, US President Donald Trump described a secret weapon in the US arsenal that he called "the discombobulator", which he said was used in the 2026 United States intervention in Venezuela to jam electronic equipment used by the Venezuelan military.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Analysts noted that what Trump described most likely does not exist as a single weapon, but rather as a system of weapons.
[src:electronic-warfare/electronic-warfare] Trump later acknowledged that he made up the name "the discombobulator", because in his words, "everything was discombobulated".
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] There are two general classes of radar jamming, mechanical and electronic.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Mechanical jamming entails reflecting enemy radio signals in various ways to provide false or misleading target signals to the radar operator.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Electronic jamming works by transmitting additional radio signals towards enemy receivers, making it difficult to detect real target signals, or take advantage of known behaviors of automated systems like radar lock-on to confuse the system.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Various Electronic counter-countermeasures (ECCMs) can sometimes help radar operators maintain target detection despite jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Mechanical jamming is caused by devices that reflect or re-reflect radar energy back to the radar to produce false target returns on the operator's scope.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Mechanical jamming devices include chaff, corner reflectors, and decoys.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Electronic jamming is a form of electronic warfare where jammers radiate interfering signals toward an enemy's radar, blocking the receiver with highly concentrated energy signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The two main technique styles are noise techniques and repeater techniques.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The three types of noise jamming are spot, sweep, and barrage.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Radar noise jamming is when a radar transciever is intentionally flooded with other radar signals as "noise" to make it harder to distinguish real radar transmissions from jamming ones.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The burn-through range is the distance from the radar at which the jamming is ineffective.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] When a target is within this range, the radar receives an adequate target skin return to track it.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The burn through range is a function of the target RCS (Radar cross-section), jamming ERP (Effective radiated power), the radars ERP and required J/S (for the jamming to be effective).
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] In some cases, jamming of either type may be caused by friendly sources.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Inadvertent mechanical jamming is fairly common because it is indiscriminate and affects any nearby radars, hostile or not.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Electronic jamming can also be inadvertently caused by friendly sources, usually powerful EW platforms operating within range of the affected radar.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Electronic counter-countermeasures (ECCMs) are used to reduce or completely suppress the effects of radar jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] For protective jamming, a small radar cross section $\sigma$ of the protected aircraft will increase the Jam-to-Signal ratio $J/S$ .
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] A lower RCS also reduces the "burn-through" range.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Stealth technologies like radiation-absorbent materials can be used to reduce the return of a target.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] While not usually caused by the enemy, interference can greatly impede the ability of an operator to track.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Interference occurs when two radars in relatively close proximity (how close they need to be depends on the power of the radars) are operating on the same frequency.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] This will cause "running rabbits", a visual phenomenon that can severely clutter up a radar display scope with useless data.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Interference is not that common between ground radars, however, because they are not usually placed close enough together.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] It is more likely that some sort of airborne radar system is inadvertently causing the interference—especially when two or more countries are involved.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The interference between airborne radars referred to above can sometimes (usually) be eliminated by frequency-shifting transmitters.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The other interference often experienced is between the aircraft's own electronic transmitters, i.e. transponders, being picked up by its radar.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] This interference is eliminated by suppressing the radar's reception for the duration of the transponder's transmission.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Instead of "bright-light" rabbits across the display, one would observe very small black dots.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Because the external radar causing the transponder to respond is generally not synchronised with your own radar (i.e. different pulse-repetition frequencies), these black dots appear randomly across the display and the operator sees through and around them.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The returning image may be much larger than the "dot" or "hole", as it has become known, anyway.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Keeping the transponder's pulse widths very narrow and mode of operation (single pulse rather than multi-pulse) becomes a crucial factor.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The external radar could, in theory, come from an aircraft flying alongside your own, or from space.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Another factor often overlooked is to reduce the sensitivity of one's own transponder to external radars; i.e., ensure that the transponder's threshold is high.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] In this way it will only respond to nearby radars—which, after all, should be friendly.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] One should also reduce the power output of the transponder in like manner.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Jamming radar for the purpose of defeating police radar guns is more simple than military-grade radar jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The laws about jamming police radars vary by jurisdiction.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] The jamming of bat sonar by certain tiger moth species has been confirmed.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] This can be seen as nature's equivalent of radar jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/radar-jamming-and-deception] Similar to human ECCM techniques, bats are found to change their emission lengths to defeat jamming.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Electronic interceptions appeared as early as 1900, during the Boer War of 1899–1902.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The British Royal Navy had installed wireless sets produced by Marconi on board their ships in the late 1890s, and the British Army used some limited wireless signalling.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The Boers captured some wireless sets and used them to make vital transmissions.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Since the British were the only people transmitting at the time, the British did not need special interpretation of the signals that they were.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The birth of signals intelligence in a modern sense dates from the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] As the Russian fleet prepared for conflict with Japan in 1904, the British ship HMS *Diana* stationed in the Suez Canal intercepted Russian naval wireless signals being sent out for the mobilization of the fleet, for the first time in history.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Over the course of the First World War, a new method of signals intelligence reached maturity.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Russia's failure to properly protect its communications fatally compromised the Russian Army's advance early in World War I and led to their disastrous defeat by the Germans under Ludendorff and Hindenburg at the Battle of Tannenberg.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In 1918, French intercept personnel captured a message written in the new ADFGVX cipher, which was cryptanalyzed by Georges Painvin.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] This gave the Allies advance warning of the German 1918 Spring Offensive.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The British in particular, built up great expertise in the newly emerging field of signals intelligence and codebreaking (synonymous with cryptanalysis).
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] On the declaration of war, Britain cut all German undersea cables.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] This forced the Germans to communicate exclusively via either (A) a telegraph line that connected through the British network and thus could be tapped; or (B) through radio which the British could then intercept.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Rear Admiral Henry Oliver appointed Sir Alfred Ewing to establish an interception and decryption service at the Admiralty; Room 40.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] An interception service known as 'Y' service, together with the post office and Marconi stations, grew rapidly to the point where the British could intercept almost all official German messages.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The German fleet was in the habit each day of wirelessing the exact position of each ship and giving regular position reports when at sea.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] It was possible to build up a precise picture of the normal operation of the High Seas Fleet, to infer from the routes they chose where defensive minefields had been placed and where it was safe for ships to operate.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Whenever a change to the normal pattern was seen, it immediately signalled that some operation was about to take place, and a warning could be given.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Detailed information about submarine movements was also available.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The use of radio-receiving equipment to pinpoint the location of any single transmitter was also developed during the war.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Round, working for Marconi, began carrying out experiments with direction-finding radio equipment for the army in France in 1915.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] By May 1915, the Admiralty was able to track German submarines crossing the North Sea.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Some of these stations also acted as 'Y' stations to collect German messages, but a new section was created within Room 40 to plot the positions of ships from the directional reports.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Room 40 played an important role in several naval engagements during the war, notably in detecting major German sorties into the North Sea.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The battle of Dogger Bank was won in no small part due to the intercepts that allowed the Navy to position its ships in the right place.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] It played a vital role in subsequent naval clashes, including at the Battle of Jutland as the British fleet was sent out to intercept them.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The direction-finding capability allowed for the tracking and location of German ships, submarines, and Zeppelins.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The system was so successful that by the end of the war, over 80 million words, comprising the totality of German wireless transmission over the course of the war, had been intercepted by the operators of the Y-stations and decrypted.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] However, its most astonishing success was in decrypting the Zimmermann Telegram, a telegram from the German Foreign Office sent via Washington to its ambassador Heinrich von Eckardt in Mexico.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] With the importance of interception and decryption firmly established by the wartime experience, countries established permanent agencies dedicated to this task in the interwar period.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In 1919, the British Cabinet's Secret Service Committee, chaired by Lord Curzon, recommended that a peace-time codebreaking agency should be created.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] GC&CS officially formed on 1 November 1919, and produced its first decrypt on 19 October.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] By 1940, GC&CS was working on the diplomatic codes and ciphers of 26 countries, tackling over 150 diplomatic cryptosystems.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The US Cipher Bureau was established in 1919 and achieved some success at the Washington Naval Conference in 1921, through cryptanalysis by Herbert Yardley.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The use of SIGINT had even greater implications during World War II.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The combined effort of intercepts and cryptanalysis for the whole of the British forces in World War II came under the code name "Ultra", managed from Government Code and Cypher School at Bletchley Park.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Properly used, the German Enigma and Lorenz ciphers should have been virtually unbreakable, but flaws in German cryptographic procedures, and poor discipline among the personnel carrying them out, created vulnerabilities which made Bletchley's attacks feasible.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Bletchley's work was essential to defeating the U-boats in the Battle of the Atlantic, and to the British naval victories in the Battle of Cape Matapan and the Battle of North Cape.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In 1941, Ultra exerted a powerful effect on the North African desert campaign against German forces under General Erwin Rommel.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] General Sir Claude Auchinleck wrote that were it not for Ultra, "Rommel would have certainly got through to Cairo".
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Ultra decrypts featured prominently in the story of Operation SALAM, László Almásy's mission across the desert behind Allied lines in 1942.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Prior to the Normandy landings on D-Day in June 1944, the Allies knew the locations of all but two of Germany's fifty-eight Western Front divisions.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Winston Churchill was reported to have told King George VI: "It is thanks to the secret weapon of General Menzies, put into use on all the fronts, that we won the war!" Supreme Allied Commander, Dwight D.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Eisenhower, at the end of the war, described Ultra as having been "decisive" to Allied victory.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Official historian of British Intelligence in World War II Sir Harry Hinsley argued that Ultra shortened the war "by not less than two years and probably by four years"; and that, in the absence of Ultra, it is uncertain how the war would have ended.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] At a lower level, German cryptanalysis, direction finding, and traffic analysis were vital to Rommel's early successes in the Western Desert Campaign until British forces tightened their communications discipline and Australian raiders destroyed his principal SIGINT Company.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Intelligence derived from communications, electronic, and foreign instrumentation signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Being a broad field, SIGINT has many sub-disciplines.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The two main ones are communications intelligence (COMINT) and electronic intelligence (ELINT).
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A collection system has to know to look for a particular signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] "System", in this context, has several nuances.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] An intelligence need considered in the allocation of intelligence resources.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] and other intelligence needs of a commander, or an agency.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Basic countermeasures against interception include frequent changing of radio frequency, polarization, and other transmission characteristics.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] An intercept aircraft could not get off the ground if it had to carry antennas and receivers for every possible frequency and signal type to deal with such countermeasures.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Second, locating the transmitter's position is usually part of SIGINT.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Triangulation and more sophisticated radio location techniques, such as time of arrival methods, require multiple receiving points at different locations.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] These receivers send location-relevant information to a central point, or perhaps to a distributed system in which all participate, such that the information can be correlated and a location computed.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Modern SIGINT systems, therefore, have substantial communications among intercept platforms.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Even if some platforms are clandestine, there is still a broadcast of information telling them where and how to look for signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A United States targeting system under development in the late 1990s, PSTS, constantly sends out information that helps the interceptors properly aim their antennas and tune their receivers.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Larger intercept aircraft, such as the EP-3 or RC-135, have the on-board capability to do some target analysis and planning, but others, such as the RC-12 GUARDRAIL, are completely under ground direction.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] GUARDRAIL aircraft are fairly small and usually work in units of three to cover a tactical SIGINT requirement, whereas the larger aircraft tend to be assigned strategic/national missions.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Before the detailed process of targeting begins, someone has to decide there is a value in collecting information about something.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] While it would be possible to direct signals intelligence collection at a major sports event, the systems would capture a great deal of noise, news signals, and perhaps announcements in the stadium.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If, however, an anti-terrorist organization believed that a small group would be trying to coordinate their efforts using short-range unlicensed radios at the event, SIGINT targeting of radios of that type would be reasonable.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Targeting would not know where in the stadium the radios might be located or the exact frequency they are using; those are the functions of subsequent steps such as signal detection and direction finding.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Once the decision to target is made, the various interception points need to cooperate, since resources are limited.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Knowing what interception equipment to use becomes easier when a target country buys its radars and radios from known manufacturers, or is given them as military aid.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] National intelligence services keep libraries of devices manufactured by their own country and others, and then use a variety of techniques to learn what equipment is acquired by a given country.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Knowledge of physics and electronic engineering further narrows the problem of what types of equipment might be in use.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] An intelligence aircraft flying well outside the borders of another country will listen for long-range search radars, not short-range fire control radars that would be used by a mobile air defense.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Soldiers scouting the front lines of another army know that the other side will be using radios that must be portable and not have huge antennas.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Even if a signal is human communications (e.g., a radio), the intelligence collection specialists have to know it exists.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If the targeting function described above learns that a country has a radar that operates in a certain frequency range, the first step is to use a sensitive receiver, with one or more antennas that listen in every direction, to find an area where such a radar is operating.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Once the radar is known to be in the area, the next step is to find its location.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If operators know the probable frequencies of transmissions of interest, they may use a set of receivers, preset to the frequencies of interest.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] These are the frequency (horizontal axis) versus power (vertical axis) produced at the transmitter, before any filtering of signals that do not add to the information being transmitted.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Received energy on a particular frequency may start a recorder, and alert a human to listen to the signals if they are intelligible (i.e., COMINT).
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If the frequency is not known, the operators may look for power on primary or sideband frequencies using a spectrum analyzer.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Information from the spectrum analyzer is then used to tune receivers to signals of interest.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] For example, in this simplified spectrum, the actual information is at 800 kHz and 1.2 MHz.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Real-world transmitters and receivers usually are directional.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In the figure to the left, assume that each display is connected to a spectrum analyzer connected to a directional antenna aimed in the indicated direction.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Spread-spectrum communications is an electronic counter-countermeasures (ECCM) technique to defeat looking for particular frequencies.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Spectrum analysis can be used in a different ECCM way to identify frequencies not being jammed or not in use.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The earliest, and still common, means of direction finding is to use directional antennas as goniometers, so that a line can be drawn from the receiver through the position of the signal of interest.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] (See HF/DF.) Knowing the compass bearing, from a single point, to the transmitter does not locate it.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Where the bearings from multiple points, using goniometry, are plotted on a map, the transmitter will be located at the point where the bearings intersect.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] This is the simplest case; a target may try to confuse listeners by having multiple transmitters, giving the same signal from different locations, switching on and off in a pattern known to their user but apparently random to the listener.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Individual directional antennas have to be manually or automatically turned to find the signal direction, which may be too slow when the signal is of short duration.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] One alternative is the Wullenweber array technique.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In this method, several concentric rings of antenna elements simultaneously receive the signal, so that the best bearing will ideally be clearly on a single antenna or a small set.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Wullenweber arrays for high-frequency signals are enormous, referred to as "elephant cages" by their users.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A more advance approach is Amplitude comparison.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] An alternative to tunable directional antennas or large omnidirectional arrays such as the Wullenweber is to measure the time of arrival of the signal at multiple points, using GPS or a similar method to have precise time synchronization.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Receivers can be on ground stations, ships, aircraft, or satellites, giving great flexibility.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A more accurate approach is Interferometer.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Modern anti-radiation missiles can home in on and attack transmitters; military antennas are rarely a safe distance from the user of the transmitter.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] When locations are known, usage patterns may emerge, from which inferences may be drawn.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Message content other than the sender and receiver is not necessary to do traffic analysis, although more information can be helpful.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] For example, if a certain type of radio is known to be used only by tank units, even if the position is not precisely determined by direction finding, it may be assumed that a tank unit is in the general area of the signal.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The owner of the transmitter can assume someone is listening, so might set up tank radios in an area where he wants the other side to believe he has actual tanks.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] As part of Operation Quicksilver, part of the deception plan for the invasion of Europe at the Battle of Normandy, radio transmissions simulated the headquarters and subordinate units of the fictitious First United States Army Group (FUSAG), commanded by George S.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Patton, to make the German defense think that the main invasion was to come at another location.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In like manner, fake radio transmissions from Japanese aircraft carriers, before the Battle of Pearl Harbor, were made from Japanese local waters, while the attacking ships moved under strict radio silence.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Traffic analysis need not focus on human communications.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] For example, a sequence of a radar signal, followed by an exchange of targeting data and a confirmation, followed by observation of artillery fire, may identify an automated counterbattery fire system.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A radio signal that triggers navigational beacons could be a radio landing aid for an airstrip or helicopter pad that is intended to be low-profile.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A radio signal with certain characteristics, originating from a fixed headquarters, may strongly suggest that a particular unit will soon move out of its regular base.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The contents of the message need not be known to infer the movement.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] There is an art as well as science of traffic analysis.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Expert analysts develop a sense for what is real and what is deceptive.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Harry Kidder, for example, was one of the star cryptanalysts of World War II, a star hidden behind the secret curtain of SIGINT.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Generating an **electronic order of battle** (EOB) requires identifying SIGINT emitters in an area of interest, determining their geographic location or range of mobility, characterizing their signals, and, where possible, determining their role in the broader organizational order of battle.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The Defense Intelligence Agency maintains an EOB by location.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] TACDB: platform lists, sorted by nomenclature, which contain links to the C-E equipment complement of each platform, with links to the parametric data for each piece of equipment, military unit lists and their subordinate units with equipment used by each unit.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] For example, several voice transmitters might be identified as the command net (i.e., top commander and direct reports) in a tank battalion or tank-heavy task force.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Another set of transmitters might identify the logistic net for that same unit.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] An inventory of ELINT sources might identify the medium- and long-range counter-artillery radars in a given area.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Signals intelligence units will identify changes in the EOB, which might indicate enemy unit movement, changes in command relationships, and increases or decreases in capability.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Using the COMINT gathering method enables the intelligence officer to produce an electronic order of battle by traffic analysis and content analysis among several enemy units.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] U2 to U1, approved. please report at arrival.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] (20 minutes later) U1 to U2, all vehicles have arrived to checkpoint X.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] This sequence shows that there are two units in the battlefield, unit 1 is mobile, while unit 2 is in a higher hierarchical level, perhaps a command post.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] One can also understand that unit 1 moved from one point to another which are distant from each 20 minutes with a vehicle.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If these are regular reports over a period of time, they might reveal a patrol pattern.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Direction-finding and radio frequency MASINT could help confirm that the traffic is not deception.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Separation of the intercepted spectrum and the signals intercepted from each sensor must take place in an extremely small period of time, in order to separate the different signals to different transmitters in the battlefield.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The complexity of the separation process depends on the complexity of the transmission methods (e.g., hopping or time-division multiple access (TDMA)).
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] By gathering and clustering data from each sensor, the measurements of the direction of signals can be optimized and get much more accurate than the basic measurements of a standard direction finding sensor.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] By calculating larger samples of the sensor's output data in near real-time, together with historical information of signals, better results are achieved.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Data fusion correlates data samples from different frequencies from the same sensor, "same" being confirmed by direction finding or radiofrequency MASINT.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If an emitter is mobile, direction finding, other than discovering a repetitive pattern of movement, is of limited value in determining if a sensor is unique.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] MASINT then becomes more informative, as individual transmitters and antennas may have unique side lobes, unintentional radiation, pulse timing, etc.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] COMINT (**com**munications **int**elligence) is a sub-category of signals intelligence that engages in dealing with messages or voice information derived from the interception of foreign communications.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] COMINT is commonly referred to as SIGINT, which can cause confusion when talking about the broader intelligence disciplines.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The US Joint Chiefs of Staff defines it as "Technical information and intelligence derived from foreign communications by other than the intended recipients".
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If the transmission is encrypted or not, and if it can be decrypted.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If it is possible to intercept either an originally transmitted cleartext or obtain it through cryptanalysis, the language of the communication and a translation (when needed).
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The addresses, if the signal is not a general broadcast and if addresses are retrievable from the message.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] These stations may also be COMINT (e.g., a confirmation of the message or a response message), ELINT (e.g., a navigation beacon being activated) or both.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Rather than, or in addition to, an address or other identifier, there may be information on the location and signal characteristics of the responder.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A basic COMINT technique is to listen for voice communications, usually over radio but possibly "leaking" from telephones or from wiretaps.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If the voice communications are encrypted, traffic analysis may still give information.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In the Second World War, for security the United States used Native American volunteer communicators known as code talkers, who used languages such as Navajo, Comanche and Choctaw, which would be understood by few people, even in the U.S.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Even within these uncommon languages, the code talkers used specialized codes, so a "butterfly" might be a specific Japanese aircraft.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] British forces made limited use of Welsh speakers for the same reason.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] While modern electronic encryption does away with the need for armies to use obscure languages, it is likely that some groups might use rare dialects that few outside their ethnic group would understand.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Morse code interception was once very important, but Morse code telegraphy is now obsolete in the western world, although possibly used by special operations forces.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Such forces, however, now have portable cryptographic equipment.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Specialists scan radio frequencies for character sequences (e.g., electronic mail) and fax.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A given digital communications link can carry thousands or millions of voice communications, especially in developed countries.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Without addressing the legality of such actions, the problem of identifying which channel contains which conversation becomes much simpler when the first thing intercepted is the *signaling channel* that carries information to set up telephone calls.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In civilian and many military use, this channel will carry messages in Signaling System 7 protocols.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Retrospective analysis of telephone calls can be made from Call detail record (CDR) used for billing the calls.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] More a part of communications security than true intelligence collection, SIGINT units still may have the responsibility of monitoring one's own communications or other electronic emissions, to avoid providing intelligence to the enemy.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] For example, a security monitor may hear an individual transmitting inappropriate information over an unencrypted radio network, or simply one that is not authorized for the type of information being given.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] If immediately calling attention to the violation would not create an even greater security risk, the monitor will call out one of the BEADWINDOW codes used by Australia, Canada, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, the United States, and other nations working under their procedures.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] **Capabilities:** "Friendly or enemy capabilities or limitations.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Force compositions or significant casualties to special equipment, weapons systems, sensors, units or personnel.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] **Operations:** "Friendly or enemy operation – intentions progress, or results.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] **Electronic warfare (EW):** "Friendly or enemy electronic warfare (EW) or emanations control (EMCON) intentions, progress, or results.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] **Communications security (COMSEC):** "Friendly or enemy COMSEC breaches.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] **Wrong circuit:** "Inappropriate transmission.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Other codes as appropriate for the situation may be defined by the commander.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] In WWII, for example, the Japanese Navy, by poor practice, identified a key person's movement over a low-security cryptosystem.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] This made possible Operation Vengeance, the interception and death of the Combined Fleet commander, Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Electronic signals intelligence (ELINT) refers to intelligence-gathering by use of electronic sensors.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Its primary focus lies on non-communications signals intelligence.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Signal identification is performed by analyzing the collected parameters of a specific signal, and either matching it to known criteria, or recording it as a possible new emitter.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] ELINT data are usually highly classified, and are protected as such.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The data gathered are typically pertinent to the electronics of an opponent's defense network, especially the electronic parts such as radars, surface-to-air missile systems, aircraft, etc.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] ELINT can be used to detect ships and aircraft by their radar and other electromagnetic radiation; commanders have to make choices between not using radar (EMCON), intermittently using it, or using it and expecting to avoid defenses.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] ELINT can be collected from ground stations near the opponent's territory, ships off their coast, aircraft near or in their airspace, or by satellite.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Combining other sources of information and ELINT allows traffic analysis to be performed on electronic emissions which contain human encoded messages.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The method of analysis differs from SIGINT in that any human encoded message which is in the electronic transmission is not analyzed during ELINT.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] What is of interest is the type of electronic transmission and its location.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] For example, during the Battle of the Atlantic in World War II, Ultra COMINT was not always available because Bletchley Park was not always able to read the U-boat Enigma traffic.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] But high-frequency direction finding ("huff-duff") was still able to detect U-boats by analysis of radio transmissions and the positions through triangulation from the direction located by two or more huff-duff systems.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The Admiralty was able to use this information to plot courses which took convoys away from high concentrations of U-boats.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Other ELINT disciplines include intercepting and analyzing enemy weapons control signals, or the identification, friend or foe responses from transponders in aircraft used to distinguish enemy craft from friendly ones.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] A very common area of ELINT is intercepting radars and learning their locations and operating procedures.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Attacking forces may be able to avoid the coverage of certain radars, or, knowing their characteristics, electronic warfare units may jam radars or send them deceptive signals.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Confusing a radar electronically is called a "soft kill", but military units will also send specialized missiles at radars, or bomb them, to get a "hard kill".
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Some modern air-to-air missiles also have radar homing guidance systems, particularly for use against large airborne radars.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Knowing where each surface-to-air missile and anti-aircraft artillery system is and its type means that air raids can be plotted to avoid the most heavily defended areas and to fly on a flight profile which will give the aircraft the best chance of evading ground fire and fighter patrols.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] It also allows for the jamming or spoofing of the enemy's defense network (see electronic warfare).
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Good electronic intelligence can be very important to stealth operations; stealth aircraft are not totally undetectable and need to know which areas to avoid.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Similarly, conventional aircraft need to know where fixed or semi-mobile air defense systems are so that they can shut them down or fly around them.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Meaconing is the combined intelligence and electronic warfare of learning the characteristics of enemy navigation aids, such as radio beacons, and retransmitting them with incorrect information.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] FISINT (Foreign instrumentation signals intelligence) is a sub-category of SIGINT, monitoring primarily non-human communication.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Foreign instrumentation signals include (but not limited to) telemetry (TELINT), tracking systems, and video data links.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] TELINT is an important part of national means of technical verification for arms control.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Still at the research level are techniques that can only be described as counter-ELINT, which would be part of a SEAD campaign.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] It may be informative to compare and contrast counter-ELINT with ECCM.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Signals intelligence and measurement and signature intelligence (MASINT) are closely, and sometimes confusingly, related.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The signals intelligence disciplines of communications and electronic intelligence focus on the information in those signals themselves, as with COMINT detecting the speech in a voice communication or ELINT measuring the frequency, pulse repetition rate, and other characteristics of a radar.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] MASINT also works with collected signals, but is more of an analysis discipline.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] There are, however, unique MASINT sensors, typically working in different regions or domains of the electromagnetic spectrum, such as infrared or magnetic fields.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] While NSA and other agencies have MASINT groups, the Central MASINT Office is in the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA).
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Where COMINT and ELINT focus on the intentionally transmitted part of the signal, MASINT focuses on unintentionally transmitted information.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] For example, a given radar antenna will have sidelobes emanating from a direction other than that in which the main antenna is aimed.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] The RADINT (radar intelligence) discipline involves learning to recognize a radar both by its primary signal, captured by ELINT, and its sidelobes, perhaps captured by the main ELINT sensor, or, more likely, a sensor aimed at the sides of the radio antenna.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] MASINT associated with COMINT might involve the detection of common background sounds expected with human voice communications.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] See HF/DF for a discussion of SIGINT-captured information with a MASINT flavor, such as determining the frequency to which a *receiver* is tuned, from detecting the frequency of the beat frequency oscillator of the superheterodyne receiver.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Since the invention of the radio, the international consensus has been that the radio-waves are no one's property, and thus the interception itself is not illegal.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] There can, however, be national laws on who is allowed to collect, store, and process radio traffic, and for what purposes.
[src:electronic-warfare/signals-intelligence] Monitoring traffic in cables (i.e. telephone and Internet) is far more controversial, since it most of the time requires physical access to the cable and thereby violating ownership and expected privacy.
